{"title_page": "Shiv Nadar", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shiv Nadar\n| image              = Shiv Nadar1.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1945|07|14}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Famous Indians of the 20th century|publisher=Pustak Mahal|last=Sharma|first=Vishwamitra|year=2003|location=New Delhi =81-223-0829-5|page=220}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Moolaipozhi|Moolaipozhi Village]], [[Tuticorin district]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India\n| residence          = [[New Delhi]]\n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Founder and chairman of [[HCL Technologies]]<br>Founder of [[SSN College of Engineering]]\n| alma_mater         = [[PSG College of Technology]]\n| networth           = US$16.1 billion (February 2020)<ref name=\"forbes1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/shiv-nadar/|title=Forbes profile: Shiv Nadar|work=Forbes |accessdate= 13 February 2020}}</ref>\n| parents            = \n| spouse             = [[Kiran Nadar]]\n| children           = [[Roshni Nadar]]\n| awards             = [[Padma Bhushan]] (2008)\n| website            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Shiv ''' (born 14 July 1945) is an Indian [[billionaire]] industrialist and philanthropist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mybtechlife.com/the-list-of-great-entrepreneurs-in-india-2015/ |title=The List of Great Entrepreneurs of India in 2015 |publisher=MyBTechLife |author=Srikar Muthyala |date=29 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114000446/http://mybtechlife.com/the-list-of-great-entrepreneurs-in-india-2015/ |archivedate=14 January 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> He is the founder and chairman of [[HCL Enterprise|HCL]] and the Shiv  Foundation. Shiv founded HCL in the mid-1970s and transformed the IT hardware company into an IT enterprise over the next three decades by constantly reinventing his company's focus. In 2008,shiv was awarded [[Padma Bhushan]] for his efforts in the IT industry.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmha.nic.in%2Fsites%2Fupload_files%2Fmha%2Ffiles%2FLST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Nadar, nicknamed by friends as ''[[Magus]]'' ([[Persian language|Old Persian]] for \"[[Wizard (fantasy)|wizard]]\"),<ref name=\"rediff2001\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2001/aug/09nadar.htm|title=Shiv Nadar completes 25 years of success|publisher=[[Rediff]]|author=Arvind Padmanabham| accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref> since the mid-1990s has focused his efforts on developing the educational system of India through the Shiv Nadar Foundation.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/shiv-nadar-foundation-forays-into-elementary-education/449223/\n | title = Shiv Nadar Foundation forays into elementary education\n | author = Vijay\n | publisher = Machinist.in\n | date = 15 September 2011\n | accessdate = 6 December 2011\n}}</ref>\n[[Ramanichandran]], a prolific Tamil romance novelist is his cousin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/ramanichandrantamilauthor/life-story|title=Ramanichandran's Life story}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nNadar was born in 1945 in [[Moolaipozhi|Moolaipozhi Village]], about {{convert|10|km|mi}} from [[Tiruchendur]] in [[Thoothukudi district]] (present), [[Tamil Nadu]], India.{{fact|date=June 2017}} His parents were Sivasubramaniya Nadar and Vamasundari Devi.<ref>{{cite book | title=India Inc: how India's top ten entrepreneurs are winning globally| edition=| author=Vikas Pota| page=179| publisher=Nicholas Brealey Publishing, 2009| isbn=1-85788-524-4}}</ref> His mother, Vamasundari Devi, is the sister of [[S. P. Adithanar]], founder of ''[[Dina Thanthi]]'' newspaper.\n\nNadar studied at [[Town Higher Secondary School]], Kumbakonam.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://thsskumbakonam.com/prominent-students.php | title=Prominent Students of Our School | accessdate=19 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Also, studied in Elango Corporation Higher Secondary School, Madurai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Madurai/elango-corporation-schools-alumnus-shiv-nadar-hcl-founder/article28797547.ece |title=Elango Corporation School's old students Shiv Nadar, the founder-chairman of HCL |publisher=The Hindu |date= |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> He was admitted into the first form (Sixth Standard) in June 1955 and continued his education in Town High School until June 1957. Later, he joined [[St. Joseph Boys Higher Secondary School, Trichy]], and completed high school education here.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/trichy/nadar-says-hindi-shaped-his-career-asks-students-to-learn-it/articleshow/67842025.cms |title=Shiv Nadar says Hindi shaped his career, asks students to learn it &#124; Trichy News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-02-05 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> Nadar received a pre-university degree in [[The American College in Madurai|the American College, Madurai]]<ref>[[American College, Madurai#Notable alumni]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=September 2019}} and a degree in Electrical and Electronics Engineering from [[PSG College of Technology]], [[Coimbatore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psgtech.edu/Shiv%20Nadar.pdf |title=Bio |publisher=www.psgtech.edu |date= |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nNadar began his career at [[Walchand group]]'s [[College of Engineering, Pune|College of Engineering, Pune (COEP)]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite book | title=India's New Capitalists: Caste, Business, and Industry in a Modern Nation| edition=| author=Harish Damodharan| date=16 September 2008| page=191| publisher=Palgrave Macmillan| isbn=978-0-230-20507-9}}</ref> he soon gave it up to begin his own venture, in partnerships with several friends and colleagues. These partners were [[Ajai Chowdhry]] (Ex-Chairman, HCL Infosystems), [[Arjun Malhotra (entrepreneur)|Arjun Malhotra]] (CEO and Chairman, Headstrong), Subhash Arora, Yogesh Vaidya, S. Raman, Mahendra Pratap and DS Puri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://infotech.indiatimes.com/articleshow/msid-1078480,prtpage-1.cms|title=Wanna be a CEO? Join HCL|date=15 April 2005|accessdate=3 April 2008|publisher=Indiatimes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216052729/http://infotech.indiatimes.com/articleshow/msid-1078480,prtpage-1.cms|archive-date=16 February 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><!-- <ref>S Raman&nbsp;\u2013 President, HCL Technologies (2003\u20132005) and ex-COO (1999\u20132003) is also referred to as a founder of the company in various forums,</ref> -->\n\nThe initial enterprise which Nadar and his partners began was Microcomp, a company which focused on selling teledigital calculators in the Indian market.<ref name=\"moneycontrol\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2007/jun/09bspec1.htm|title=The amazing story of the birth of HCL|publisher=Moneycontrol|date=9 June 2007|accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dqindia.ciol.com/content/dq_top20/2002/102072503.asp|title=HCL Group: The M&A Year|publisher=DQ Group|date=25 July 2002|accessdate=26 March 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321113809/http://dqindia.ciol.com/content/dq_top20/2002/102072503.asp|archivedate=21 March 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> HCL was founded in 1976, with an investment of Rs. 187,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dqindia.ciol.com/content/dqtop202k3/giants/103080504.asp|title=HCL GROUP&nbsp;\u2013 The Change Agents|publisher=DQ India|accessdate=26 March 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423174235/http://dqindia.ciol.com/content/dqtop202k3/giants/103080504.asp|archivedate=23 April 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, HCL ventured into the international market with the opening of Far East Computers in Singapore to sell IT hardware. The venture reported Rs 1 million revenue in the first year and continued to address the Singapore operations.<ref name=\"mcdark\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/india/news/management/shivnadarhcl/thedarkhorsetechnologysector/market/stocks/article/279967|title=The dark horse of the technology sector|publisher=Moneycontrol|date=7 May 2007|accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref> Nadar remained the largest shareholder without retaining any management control.\n\n== Focus on education and healthcare ==\n[[File:Shri Shiv Nadar and Ms Roshni Nadar presenting a cheque of Rs. 4 crore to the Prime Minister, Dr. Manmohan Singh, towards the Prime Minister's National Relief Fund in New Delhi on January 17, 2005.jpg|thumb|Shri Shiv Nadar and Ms Roshni Nadar presenting a cheque of Rs. 4 crore to the Prime Minister, Dr. Manmohan Singh, towards the Prime Minister's National Relief Fund in New Delhi on January 17, 2005]]\nIn 1996, Nadar founded [[SSN College of Engineering]] in [[Chennai]], Tamil Nadu in the name of his father, Sivasubramaniya Nadar. Nadar took an active role in the college activities, including the gifting of Rs. 1 million worth of HCL shares to the college.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/businessline/ew/2001/07/25/stories/0125a203.htm |title=Shiv Nadar gifts HCL Tech shares to Chennai Trust |work=The Hindu |location=India |date=25 July 2001 |accessdate=26 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030513060340/http://www.hinduonnet.com/businessline/ew/2001/07/25/stories/0125a203.htm |archivedate=13 May 2003 }}</ref> In 2006, Nadar announced that the college will promote research apart from ensuring that students benefit from foreign university tie-ups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/03/01/stories/2006030114710500.htm|title=SSN engineering college to step up high-end research |work=The Hindu |location=India|date=1 March 2006|accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref> Nadar joined the executive board of [[Indian School of Business]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2005/10/05/stories/2005100503100900.htm|title=Shiv Nadar joins ISB executive board|work=The Hindu|location=India|date=5 October 2004|accessdate=26 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930230146/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2005/10/05/stories/2005100503100900.htm|archive-date=30 September 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In March 2008, Nadar's SSN Trust announced the setting up of two Vidyagyan schools in UP for rural students, where free scholarship will be provided for 200 students from 50 districts of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. He visited Town Higher Secondary School in February 2011 and donated computers and other equipment worth Rs. 80 lakhs. He served as chairman of the board of governors, IIT Kharagpur, a technical institute until 2014.{{fact|date=June 2017}}\n\n==Personal life==\nHis only daughter [[Roshni Nadar]] is vice-chairman of HCL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/hcl-gen-next-roshni-nadar-appointed-vice-chairman-of-hcl-tech/articleshow/66335013.cms|title=HCL gen-next Roshni Nadar appointed vice-chairman of HCL Tech}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and accolades ==\n\nIn 2008, the government of India awarded Nadar with a [[Padma Bhushan]], the third highest civilian award, for his contribution to the IT industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/News/News_By_Company/Corporate_Trends/India_Inc_shines_on_civilian_honour_rolls/rssarticleshow/2734466.cms|title=India Inc shines on civilian honour rolls|work=The Economic Times |location=India|date=27 January 2008|accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Madras University awarded him an honorary doctorate degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/11/11/stories/2007111155170500.htm|title=Honorary doctorate for Balachander, Nadar|work=The Hindu |location=India|date=11 November 2007|accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref> Nadar was also recognised as E&Y Entrepreneur of the Year 2007 (Services).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ey.com/GLOBAL/content.nsf/India/EOY_2007_Winner_shiv_Nadar|archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20081113053536/http://www.ey.com/GLOBAL/content.nsf/India/EOY_2007_Winner_Shiv_Nadar|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 November 2008|title=Honorary Entrepreneur Of The Year 2007&nbsp;\u2013 Services|publisher=[[Ernst & Young]]|accessdate=26 March 2008}} </ref>\n \nIn 1995 he became the Dataquest IT Man of the year.{{fact|date=June 2017}} the In 2005 he was bestowed with CNBC Business Excellence Award.{{fact|date=June 2017}} In 2006 he received an honorary fellowship from the All India Management Association.{{fact|date=June 2017}} In 2011 he was counted amongst ''Forbes''{{'}} 48 Heroes of Philanthropy in Asia Pacific.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2011/0718/heroes-philanthropy-11-kaldor-zhiqiang-oberoi-heroes-list.html|title=48 Heroes Of Philanthropy|last=Staff|first=Forbes Asia|date=2011-06-22|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-08-08|language=en}}</ref> In 2010 he received the Dataquest Lifetime Achievement Award.{{fact|date=June 2017}} <!--(Commenting this out because it's incomplete. I couldn't figure it out by googling. If you can complete this, please do. Thanks!)  In 2011 he was listed in Forbes Entrepreneurs of the -->\n\nIn April 2017, [[India Today]] magazine ranked Nadar #16th in India's 50 most powerful people of 2017 list.<ref>{{cite news|title=India's 50 powerful people|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/india-today-top-50-powerful-indians-mukesh-ambani-ratan-tata-kumar-mangalam-birla-gautam-adani-anand-mahindra-srk-amitabh-bacchan/1/928939.html|publisher=[[India Today]]|date=April 14, 2017}}</ref> Nadar has committed more than $1 billion to philanthropy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/anuraghunathan/2016/07/06/shiv-nadars-vidyagyan-lands-rural-indian-kids-in-leading-institutes-from-engineering-to-fashion/#7adf6b512903|title=Shiv Nadar's VidyaGyan Lands Rural Indian Kids In Leading Institutes -From Engineering To Fashion|last=Raghunathan|first=Anu|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-08-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.hcl.com/leadership/hcl-corporation Profile] at [[HCL Enterprise|HCL]]\n* [https://www.forbes.com/profile/shiv-nadar Profile] at ''[[Forbes]]''\n* [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/shiv-Nadar Shiv Nadar] collected news and commentary at ''[[The Times of India]]''\n* [http://knowledge.wharton.upenn.edu/article.cfm?articleid=1558 K@W interview with Shiv Nadar]\n* [http://cnn.com/2005/WORLD/asiapcf/12/14/talkasia.nadar.script/ CNN interview with Shiv Nadar]\n\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2000\u201309|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nadar, Shiv}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Indian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Indian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Tamil billionaires]]\n[[Category:Tamil entrepreneurs]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in trade and industry]]\n[[Category:Tamil businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Thoothukudi district]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Indian Tamil people]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shiv Nadar\n| image              = Shiv Nadar1.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1945|07|14}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Famous Indians of the 20th century|publisher=Pustak Mahal|last=Sharma|first=Vishwamitra|year=2003|location=New Delhi =81-223-0829-5|page=220}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Moolaipozhi|Moolaipozhi Village]], [[Tuticorin district]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India\n| residence          = [[New Delhi]]\n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Founder and chairman of [[HCL Technologies]]<br>Founder of [[SSN College of Engineering]]\n| alma_mater         = [[PSG College of Technology]]\n| networth           = US$16.1 billion (February 2020)<ref name=\"forbes1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/shiv-nadar/|title=Forbes profile: Shiv Nadar|work=Forbes |accessdate= 13 February 2020}}</ref>\n| parents            = \n| spouse             = [[Kiran Nadar]]\n| children           = [[Roshni Nadar]]\n| awards             = [[Padma Bhushan]] (2008)\n| website            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Shiv Nadar''' (born 14 July 1945) is an Indian [[billionaire]] industrialist and philanthropist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mybtechlife.com/the-list-of-great-entrepreneurs-in-india-2015/ |title=The List of Great Entrepreneurs of India in 2015 |publisher=MyBTechLife |author=Srikar Muthyala |date=29 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114000446/http://mybtechlife.com/the-list-of-great-entrepreneurs-in-india-2015/ |archivedate=14 January 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> He is the founder and chairman of [[HCL Enterprise|HCL]] and the Shiv Nadar Foundation. Nadar founded HCL in the mid-1970s and transformed the IT hardware company into an IT enterprise over the next three decades by constantly reinventing his company's focus. In 2008, Nadar was awarded [[Padma Bhushan]] for his efforts in the IT industry.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=July 21, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmha.nic.in%2Fsites%2Fupload_files%2Fmha%2Ffiles%2FLST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Nadar, nicknamed by friends as ''[[Magus]]'' ([[Persian language|Old Persian]] for \"[[Wizard (fantasy)|wizard]]\"),<ref name=\"rediff2001\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2001/aug/09nadar.htm|title=Shiv Nadar completes 25 years of success|publisher=[[Rediff]]|author=Arvind Padmanabham| accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref> since the mid-1990s has focused his efforts on developing the educational system of India through the Shiv Nadar Foundation.<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/shiv-nadar-foundation-forays-into-elementary-education/449223/\n | title = Shiv Nadar Foundation forays into elementary education\n | author = Vijay\n | publisher = Machinist.in\n | date = 15 September 2011\n | accessdate = 6 December 2011\n}}</ref>\n[[Ramanichandran]], a prolific Tamil romance novelist is his cousin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/ramanichandrantamilauthor/life-story|title=Ramanichandran's Life story}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\n\nNadar was born in 1945 in [[Moolaipozhi|Moolaipozhi Village]], about {{convert|10|km|mi}} from [[Tiruchendur]] in [[Thoothukudi district]] (present), [[Tamil Nadu]], India.{{fact|date=June 2017}} His parents were Sivasubramaniya Nadar and Vamasundari Devi.<ref>{{cite book | title=India Inc: how India's top ten entrepreneurs are winning globally| edition=| author=Vikas Pota| page=179| publisher=Nicholas Brealey Publishing, 2009| isbn=1-85788-524-4}}</ref> His mother, Vamasundari Devi, is the sister of [[S. P. Adithanar]], founder of ''[[Dina Thanthi]]'' newspaper.\n\nNadar studied at [[Town Higher Secondary School]], Kumbakonam.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://thsskumbakonam.com/prominent-students.php | title=Prominent Students of Our School | accessdate=19 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Also, studied in Elango Corporation Higher Secondary School, Madurai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Madurai/elango-corporation-schools-alumnus-shiv-nadar-hcl-founder/article28797547.ece |title=Elango Corporation School's old students Shiv Nadar, the founder-chairman of HCL |publisher=The Hindu |date= |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> He was admitted into the first form (Sixth Standard) in June 1955 and continued his education in Town High School until June 1957. Later, he joined [[St. Joseph Boys Higher Secondary School, Trichy]], and completed high school education here.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/trichy/nadar-says-hindi-shaped-his-career-asks-students-to-learn-it/articleshow/67842025.cms |title=Shiv Nadar says Hindi shaped his career, asks students to learn it &#124; Trichy News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-02-05 |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> Nadar received a pre-university degree in [[The American College in Madurai|the American College, Madurai]]<ref>[[American College, Madurai#Notable alumni]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=September 2019}} and a degree in Electrical and Electronics Engineering from [[PSG College of Technology]], [[Coimbatore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psgtech.edu/Shiv%20Nadar.pdf |title=Bio |publisher=www.psgtech.edu |date= |accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nNadar began his career at [[Walchand group]]'s [[College of Engineering, Pune|College of Engineering, Pune (COEP)]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite book | title=India's New Capitalists: Caste, Business, and Industry in a Modern Nation| edition=| author=Harish Damodharan| date=16 September 2008| page=191| publisher=Palgrave Macmillan| isbn=978-0-230-20507-9}}</ref> he soon gave it up to begin his own venture, in partnerships with several friends and colleagues. These partners were [[Ajai Chowdhry]] (Ex-Chairman, HCL Infosystems), [[Arjun Malhotra (entrepreneur)|Arjun Malhotra]] (CEO and Chairman, Headstrong), Subhash Arora, Yogesh Vaidya, S. Raman, Mahendra Pratap and DS Puri.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://infotech.indiatimes.com/articleshow/msid-1078480,prtpage-1.cms|title=Wanna be a CEO? Join HCL|date=15 April 2005|accessdate=3 April 2008|publisher=Indiatimes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216052729/http://infotech.indiatimes.com/articleshow/msid-1078480,prtpage-1.cms|archive-date=16 February 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><!-- <ref>S Raman&nbsp;\u2013 President, HCL Technologies (2003\u20132005) and ex-COO (1999\u20132003) is also referred to as a founder of the company in various forums,</ref> -->\n\nThe initial enterprise which Nadar and his partners began was Microcomp, a company which focused on selling teledigital calculators in the Indian market.<ref name=\"moneycontrol\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2007/jun/09bspec1.htm|title=The amazing story of the birth of HCL|publisher=Moneycontrol|date=9 June 2007|accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dqindia.ciol.com/content/dq_top20/2002/102072503.asp|title=HCL Group: The M&A Year|publisher=DQ Group|date=25 July 2002|accessdate=26 March 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321113809/http://dqindia.ciol.com/content/dq_top20/2002/102072503.asp|archivedate=21 March 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> HCL was founded in 1976, with an investment of Rs. 187,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dqindia.ciol.com/content/dqtop202k3/giants/103080504.asp|title=HCL GROUP&nbsp;\u2013 The Change Agents|publisher=DQ India|accessdate=26 March 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423174235/http://dqindia.ciol.com/content/dqtop202k3/giants/103080504.asp|archivedate=23 April 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, HCL ventured into the international market with the opening of Far East Computers in Singapore to sell IT hardware. The venture reported Rs 1 million revenue in the first year and continued to address the Singapore operations.<ref name=\"mcdark\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/india/news/management/shivnadarhcl/thedarkhorsetechnologysector/market/stocks/article/279967|title=The dark horse of the technology sector|publisher=Moneycontrol|date=7 May 2007|accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref> Nadar remained the largest shareholder without retaining any management control.\n\n== Focus on education and healthcare ==\n[[File:Shri Shiv Nadar and Ms Roshni Nadar presenting a cheque of Rs. 4 crore to the Prime Minister, Dr. Manmohan Singh, towards the Prime Minister's National Relief Fund in New Delhi on January 17, 2005.jpg|thumb|Shri Shiv Nadar and Ms Roshni Nadar presenting a cheque of Rs. 4 crore to the Prime Minister, Dr. Manmohan Singh, towards the Prime Minister's National Relief Fund in New Delhi on January 17, 2005]]\nIn 1996, Nadar founded [[SSN College of Engineering]] in [[Chennai]], Tamil Nadu in the name of his father, Sivasubramaniya Nadar. Nadar took an active role in the college activities, including the gifting of Rs. 1 million worth of HCL shares to the college.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/businessline/ew/2001/07/25/stories/0125a203.htm |title=Shiv Nadar gifts HCL Tech shares to Chennai Trust |work=The Hindu |location=India |date=25 July 2001 |accessdate=26 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030513060340/http://www.hinduonnet.com/businessline/ew/2001/07/25/stories/0125a203.htm |archivedate=13 May 2003 }}</ref> In 2006, Nadar announced that the college will promote research apart from ensuring that students benefit from foreign university tie-ups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/03/01/stories/2006030114710500.htm|title=SSN engineering college to step up high-end research |work=The Hindu |location=India|date=1 March 2006|accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref> Nadar joined the executive board of [[Indian School of Business]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2005/10/05/stories/2005100503100900.htm|title=Shiv Nadar joins ISB executive board|work=The Hindu|location=India|date=5 October 2004|accessdate=26 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930230146/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2005/10/05/stories/2005100503100900.htm|archive-date=30 September 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In March 2008, Nadar's SSN Trust announced the setting up of two Vidyagyan schools in UP for rural students, where free scholarship will be provided for 200 students from 50 districts of [[Uttar Pradesh]]. He visited Town Higher Secondary School in February 2011 and donated computers and other equipment worth Rs. 80 lakhs. He served as chairman of the board of governors, IIT Kharagpur, a technical institute until 2014.{{fact|date=June 2017}}\n\n==Personal life==\nHis only daughter [[Roshni Nadar]] is vice-chairman of HCL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/hcl-gen-next-roshni-nadar-appointed-vice-chairman-of-hcl-tech/articleshow/66335013.cms|title=HCL gen-next Roshni Nadar appointed vice-chairman of HCL Tech}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and accolades ==\n\nIn 2008, the government of India awarded Nadar with a [[Padma Bhushan]], the third highest civilian award, for his contribution to the IT industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/News/News_By_Company/Corporate_Trends/India_Inc_shines_on_civilian_honour_rolls/rssarticleshow/2734466.cms|title=India Inc shines on civilian honour rolls|work=The Economic Times |location=India|date=27 January 2008|accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Madras University awarded him an honorary doctorate degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/11/11/stories/2007111155170500.htm|title=Honorary doctorate for Balachander, Nadar|work=The Hindu |location=India|date=11 November 2007|accessdate=26 March 2008}}</ref> Nadar was also recognised as E&Y Entrepreneur of the Year 2007 (Services).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ey.com/GLOBAL/content.nsf/India/EOY_2007_Winner_shiv_Nadar|archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20081113053536/http://www.ey.com/GLOBAL/content.nsf/India/EOY_2007_Winner_Shiv_Nadar|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 November 2008|title=Honorary Entrepreneur Of The Year 2007&nbsp;\u2013 Services|publisher=[[Ernst & Young]]|accessdate=26 March 2008}} </ref>\n \nIn 1995 he became the Dataquest IT Man of the year.{{fact|date=June 2017}} the In 2005 he was bestowed with CNBC Business Excellence Award.{{fact|date=June 2017}} In 2006 he received an honorary fellowship from the All India Management Association.{{fact|date=June 2017}} In 2011 he was counted amongst ''Forbes''{{'}} 48 Heroes of Philanthropy in Asia Pacific.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2011/0718/heroes-philanthropy-11-kaldor-zhiqiang-oberoi-heroes-list.html|title=48 Heroes Of Philanthropy|last=Staff|first=Forbes Asia|date=2011-06-22|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-08-08|language=en}}</ref> In 2010 he received the Dataquest Lifetime Achievement Award.{{fact|date=June 2017}} <!--(Commenting this out because it's incomplete. I couldn't figure it out by googling. If you can complete this, please do. Thanks!)  In 2011 he was listed in Forbes Entrepreneurs of the -->\n\nIn April 2017, [[India Today]] magazine ranked Nadar #16th in India's 50 most powerful people of 2017 list.<ref>{{cite news|title=India's 50 powerful people|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/india-today-top-50-powerful-indians-mukesh-ambani-ratan-tata-kumar-mangalam-birla-gautam-adani-anand-mahindra-srk-amitabh-bacchan/1/928939.html|publisher=[[India Today]]|date=April 14, 2017}}</ref> Nadar has committed more than $1 billion to philanthropy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/anuraghunathan/2016/07/06/shiv-nadars-vidyagyan-lands-rural-indian-kids-in-leading-institutes-from-engineering-to-fashion/#7adf6b512903|title=Shiv Nadar's VidyaGyan Lands Rural Indian Kids In Leading Institutes -From Engineering To Fashion|last=Raghunathan|first=Anu|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-08-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.hcl.com/leadership/hcl-corporation Profile] at [[HCL Enterprise|HCL]]\n* [https://www.forbes.com/profile/shiv-nadar Profile] at ''[[Forbes]]''\n* [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/shiv-Nadar Shiv Nadar] collected news and commentary at ''[[The Times of India]]''\n* [http://knowledge.wharton.upenn.edu/article.cfm?articleid=1558 K@W interview with Shiv Nadar]\n* [http://cnn.com/2005/WORLD/asiapcf/12/14/talkasia.nadar.script/ CNN interview with Shiv Nadar]\n\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2000\u201309|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nadar, Shiv}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Indian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Indian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Tamil billionaires]]\n[[Category:Tamil entrepreneurs]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in trade and industry]]\n[[Category:Tamil businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Thoothukudi district]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Indian Tamil people]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4072:593:ff7d:8e:be40:b6b5:d113", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shiv_Nadar"}
{"title_page": "Passive income", "text_new": "{{short description|Income that requires little to no effort to earn and maintain}}\n{{about|category used in accounting and taxation|subset of unearned income based on property ownership|property income|the general concept that includes property income|unearned income}}\n{{Globalize|article|USA|2name=the United States|date=May 2014}}\n'''Passive income''' is income that requires little to no effort to earn and maintain. It is called progressive passive income when the earner expends little effort to grow the income. Examples of passive income include [[rental income]] and any business activities in which the earner does not materially participate. Some jurisdictions' taxing authorities, such as the [[Internal Revenue Service]] in the [[United States of America]], distinguish passive income from other forms of income, such as earnings from regular or contractual employment, and may tax it differently.\n\n== United States of America ==\n\nThe United States [[Internal Revenue Service]] categorizes income as active income, passive income, or portfolio income.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irs.gov/publications/p550/ch03.html|title=Publication 550 \u2014 Investment Income and Expenses|last=|first=|date=|website=www.irs.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It defines passive income as only coming from two sources, or \"passive activities\": rental activity or \"trade or business activities in which you do not materially participate.\"<ref name=\"irs.gov\">[https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/p925.pdf \"Publication 925 \u2014 Passive Activity and At-Risk Rules\"] Retrieved 2019-10-19.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc425.html|title=Tax Topic 425 Passive Activities \u2014 Losses and Credits|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2009-06-18}}</ref> Other financial and government institutions also recognize it as an income obtained as a result of capital growth or in relation to [[negative gearing]]. Passive income is usually [[Taxable income|taxable]].\n\nActive income is [[earned income]] including all taxable income and wages the earner receives for working. Active income includes wages, self-employment income, and material participation in an [[S corporation]] or partnership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irs.gov/credits-deductions/individuals/earned-income-tax-credit/earned-income|title=Earned Income {{!}} Internal Revenue Service|website=www.irs.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref> Portfolio income is derived from investments such as [[Dividend|dividends]], [[interest]], [[Capital gain|capital gains]], and some [[Royalty payment|royalties]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://justaskbenwhy.com/2015/06/22/earned-income-vs-passive-income-vs-portfolio-income/|title=Earned Income vs Passive Income vs Portfolio Income: A Comparison - Just Ask Ben Why|date=2015-06-22|work=Just Ask Ben Why|access-date=2018-05-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Passive activities ===\nThere are three kinds of passive activities:\n\n* Cash flows from [[property income]], including profits from ownership of capital, rent from ownership of resources such as [[Renting|rental income]], cash flows from [[property]] or any piece of [[real estate]], and interest from owning financial assets.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irs.gov/publications/p925|title=Publication 925 (2017),  Passive Activity and At-Risk Rules {{!}} Internal Revenue Service|website=www.irs.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n* Trade or business activities in which one does not materially participate during the year.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Royalties]], which are payments made by one company (the licensee) to another company or person (the licensor) for the right to use the latter's intellectual property (book, music, video).  However, the Internal Revenue Service only considers royalties passive income when they are \"not derived in the ordinary course of a trade or business.\"<ref name=\"irs.gov\" />\n\nSome limited partnerships may be considered passive as long as the limited partner does not have any role in the company and exchanges their capital investment for a share of the activities profit.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n=== Rental activities ===\nIn order to be considered a rental activity, tangible property is used by customers and the income paid from the activity comes from the amount paid for the use of the property and is not considered a rental if:\n\n# The average period of customer use is:\n#* 7 days or less\n#* 30 days or less and significant personal services were provided\n\n== Sources of passive income ==\nThere are more types of passive income than is shown in this article. In any case, it is preferable to consult with [[ financial advisor ]] first.\n\n* [[ Bank deposit ]]\nIt is one of the most popular and simplest ways to gain passive income. A person gives a certain amount of money to a bank and takes interest every month. <ref name=\"nccp0\">{{cite web | url= https://www.investopedia.com/terms/b/bank-deposits.asp| title= Bank Deposits | date= September 19, 2019| author1=  Julia Kagan }} </ref>\n* [[ Securities ]] \nThe profit, created by security, is in general inversely proportional to the risk it holds. \n* Bonds \nBonds are debt securities issued by the state or company for gaining investments. By purchasing a bond, a person is lending savings to the issuer for a specified period. In return, he receives income at the very end of the bond validity period, or he can also earn so-called coupon income. <ref name=\"sources\">{{cite web | url=https://www.fool.com/retirement/2018/01/18/what-is-passive-income.aspx| title= What Is Passive Income? | date= January 18, 2018| author1= Maurie Backman\n}}</ref>\n* Dividend stocks\nIt is a reliable way to generate income passively. However, it is important to mention the research to find stocks with desirable risk/income ratio. <ref name=\"sources1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.dividend.com/dividend-investing-101/what-are-dividend-stocks/| title= What are Dividend Stocks? | date= February 25, 2015| author1= Shauna O'Brien\n}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Cash flow]]\n* [[Capital gains]]\n* [[Economic rent]]\n* [[Profit (economics)|Profit]]\n* [[Property income]]\n* [[Rent seeking]]\n* [[Surplus value]]\n* [[Unearned income]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wiktionary|passive income}}\n*[https://dollarpassiveincome.com/passive-income-ideas/ Passive income], DollarPassiveIncome\n* [http://www.moneysmart.gov.au/investing/investment-warnings ASIC's MoneySmart website]\n*[https://dollarpassiveincome.com/ Earn $10,000 Passive income]\n\n[[Category:Profit]]\n[[Category:Income]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Income that requires little to no effort to earn and maintain}}\n{{about|category used in accounting and taxation|subset of unearned income based on property ownership|property income|the general concept that includes property income|unearned income}}\n{{Globalize|article|USA|2name=the United States|date=May 2014}}\n'''Passive income''' is income that requires little to no effort to earn and maintain. It is called progressive passive income when the earner expends little effort to grow the income. Examples of passive income include [[rental income]] and any business activities in which the earner does not materially participate. Some jurisdictions' taxing authorities, such as the [[Internal Revenue Service]] in the [[United States of America]], distinguish passive income from other forms of income, such as earnings from regular or contractual employment, and may tax it differently.\n\n== United States of America ==\n\nThe United States [[Internal Revenue Service]] categorizes income as active income, passive income, or portfolio income.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irs.gov/publications/p550/ch03.html|title=Publication 550 \u2014 Investment Income and Expenses|last=|first=|date=|website=www.irs.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It defines passive income as only coming from two sources, or \"passive activities\": rental activity or \"trade or business activities in which you do not materially participate.\"<ref name=\"irs.gov\">[https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/p925.pdf \"Publication 925 \u2014 Passive Activity and At-Risk Rules\"] Retrieved 2019-10-19.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc425.html|title=Tax Topic 425 Passive Activities \u2014 Losses and Credits|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2009-06-18}}</ref> Other financial and government institutions also recognize it as an income obtained as a result of capital growth or in relation to [[negative gearing]]. Passive income is usually [[Taxable income|taxable]].\n\nActive income is [[earned income]] including all taxable income and wages the earner receives for working. Active income includes wages, self-employment income, and material participation in an [[S corporation]] or partnership.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irs.gov/credits-deductions/individuals/earned-income-tax-credit/earned-income|title=Earned Income {{!}} Internal Revenue Service|website=www.irs.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref> Portfolio income is derived from investments such as [[Dividend|dividends]], [[interest]], [[Capital gain|capital gains]], and some [[Royalty payment|royalties]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://justaskbenwhy.com/2015/06/22/earned-income-vs-passive-income-vs-portfolio-income/|title=Earned Income vs Passive Income vs Portfolio Income: A Comparison - Just Ask Ben Why|date=2015-06-22|work=Just Ask Ben Why|access-date=2018-05-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Passive activities ===\nThere are three kinds of passive activities:\n\n* Cash flows from [[property income]], including profits from ownership of capital, rent from ownership of resources such as [[Renting|rental income]], cash flows from [[property]] or any piece of [[real estate]], and interest from owning financial assets.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irs.gov/publications/p925|title=Publication 925 (2017),  Passive Activity and At-Risk Rules {{!}} Internal Revenue Service|website=www.irs.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n* Trade or business activities in which one does not materially participate during the year.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Royalties]], which are payments made by one company (the licensee) to another company or person (the licensor) for the right to use the latter's intellectual property (book, music, video).  However, the Internal Revenue Service only considers royalties passive income when they are \"not derived in the ordinary course of a trade or business.\"<ref name=\"irs.gov\" />\n\nSome limited partnerships may be considered passive as long as the limited partner does not have any role in the company and exchanges their capital investment for a share of the activities profit.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n=== Rental activities ===\nIn order to be considered a rental activity, tangible property is used by customers and the income paid from the activity comes from the amount paid for the use of the property and is not considered a rental if:\n\n# The average period of customer use is:\n#* 7 days or less\n#* 30 days or less and significant personal services were provided\n\n== Sources of passive income ==\nThere are more types of passive income than is shown in this article. In any case, it is preferable to consult with [[ financial advisor ]] first.\n\n* [[ Bank deposit ]]\nIt is one of the most popular and simplest ways to gain passive income. A person gives a certain amount of money to a bank and takes interest every month. <ref name=\"nccp0\">{{cite web | url= https://www.investopedia.com/terms/b/bank-deposits.asp| title= Bank Deposits | date= September 19, 2019| author1=  Julia Kagan }} </ref>\n* [[ Securities ]] \nThe profit, created by security, is in general inversely proportional to the risk it holds. \n* Bonds \nBonds are debt securities issued by the state or company for gaining investments. By purchasing a bond, a person is lending savings to the issuer for a specified period. In return, he receives income at the very end of the bond validity period, or he can also earn so-called coupon income. <ref name=\"sources\">{{cite web | url=https://www.fool.com/retirement/2018/01/18/what-is-passive-income.aspx| title= What Is Passive Income? | date= January 18, 2018| author1= Maurie Backman\n}}</ref>\n* Dividend stocks\nIt is a reliable way to generate income passively. However, it is important to mention the research to find stocks with desirable risk/income ratio. <ref name=\"sources1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.dividend.com/dividend-investing-101/what-are-dividend-stocks/| title= What are Dividend Stocks? | date= February 25, 2015| author1= Shauna O'Brien\n}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Cash flow]]\n* [[Capital gains]]\n* [[Economic rent]]\n* [[Profit (economics)|Profit]]\n* [[Property income]]\n* [[Rent seeking]]\n* [[Surplus value]]\n* [[Unearned income]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wiktionary}}\n* [http://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/passiveincome.asp Passive income], Investopedia\n* [http://www.moneysmart.gov.au/investing/investment-warnings ASIC's MoneySmart website]\n\n[[Category:Profit]]\n[[Category:Income]]\n", "name_user": "Suraj112", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passive_income"}
{"title_page": "KF Sopoti", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| nickname = Sopotar\u00ebt\n| ground =  [[Sopoti Stadium]]<br/>[[Librazhd]], [[Albania]]\n| capacity = 3,000\n| pattern_la1=TTTT\n| pattern_la2=JJJJ\n| pattern_b2=JJJJ\n| pattern_ra1=KKKKKKK\n| pattern_ra2=BBBB\n| leftarm1= 0D7301\n| leftarm2=722U2HHHH\n| body1= 0D7301\n| body2=FFFFFF\n| rightarm1= 0D7301\n| rightarm2=FFHHHHHFFFF\n| shorts1=FFFFFFFFFFFFF\n| shorts2=FFFFDFFFFFF\n| socks1= 0DO7301\n| socks2=0D78301\n| clubname = \n| image =  [[Image:Sopoti Librazhd Club Logo.svg|230px|Club crest]]\n| fullname = Klubi Sportiv Sopoti Librazhd\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1948}}\n| owntitle = President\n| owner = [[Bashkia Librazhd]] \n| chairman = [[Kastriot Gurra]] \n| manager = [[Klajdi K\u00ebnga]]\n| league = [[Albanian Second Division]]\n| season   = [[2018\u201319 Albanian Second Division|2018\u201319]]\n| position = [[Albanian Second Division]], Group A, 5th \n| pattern_b1=\n| website= \n}}\n'''KF Sopoti''' is an Albanian [[sports club]] based in [[Librazhd]]. The club currently competes in the [[Albanian Second Division]], the third tier of football in Albania.\n\n==History==\nThey were founded in 1948 under the name ''KS Albania Tabak Librazhd'', and they play their home games at the [[Sopoti Stadium]]. The club is named after the nearby [[Sopot, Albania|Sopot]] Mountain. They spent the [[1992\u201393 Albanian Superliga|1992/93]], [[1993\u201394 Albanian Superliga|1993/94]], [[1995\u201396 Albanian Superliga|1995/96]] and [[1996\u201397 Albanian Superliga|1996/97]] seasons in the [[Albanian Superliga|''Kategoria Superiore'']]. Before the 1996/97 season the changed their name back to Albania Tabak Librazhd,<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/alba97.html Albania 1996/97] - RSSSF</ref> only to change it to Sopoti Librazhd once more the next year.\n\n==Stadium==\nThe club's home ground is the multi-use [[Sopoti Stadium]] which is situated in the centre of the town next to the municipality building. The stadium which has a capacity of 3,000 spectators was built in 1964 and has been the club's home ever since. The stadium is not currently fit for use but the [[Albanian Football Association]] along with the [[Librazhd|Librazhd Municipality]] have drawn up initial plans to reconstruct the stadium in its entirety, but such plans have yet to be materialised due to a lack of funding.<ref>[http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/ngjallen-shpresat-per-stadiumin-e-librazhdit/ Ngjallen shpresat p\u00ebr stadiumin e Librazhdit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006072012/http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/ngjallen-shpresat-per-stadiumin-e-librazhdit/ |date=6 October 2014 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/sopoti-problem-ceshtja-e-stadiumit/ Sopoti, problem \u00e7\u00ebshtja e stadiumit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006092601/http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/sopoti-problem-ceshtja-e-stadiumit/ |date=6 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAs of the 2014\u201315 season the stadium does not meet the current [[Albanian Football Association]]'s standard requirements, due to the outdated and run down nature of the building as well as the field.<ref>[http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/skandal-ne-librazhd-fusha-kthehet-ne-mocal/ Skandal n\u00eb Librazhd, fusha kthehet n\u00eb \u201cmo\u00e7al\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006110520/http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/skandal-ne-librazhd-fusha-kthehet-ne-mocal/ |date=6 October 2014 }}</ref> .In 2017-18 season Kf Sopoti will play in home stadium with new coach the 25 years old ex player of Sopoti Mr. Klajdi K\u00ebnga and the players will be from age groups .\n\n==Recent seasons==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=9|League\n!rowspan=2 width=\"30\"|[[Croatian Football Cup|Cup]]\n|-\n!Division\n!width=\"25\"|P\n!width=\"25\"|W\n!width=\"25\"|D\n!width=\"25\"|L\n!width=\"25\"|F\n!width=\"25\"|A\n!width=\"25\"|Pts\n!width=\"40\"|Pos\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|[[2017\u201318 Albanian Second Division|Albanian Second Division]]\n|24\n|6\n|5\n|13\n|35\n|44\n|23\n|10th<small>/14</small>\n|[[2018\u201319 Albanian Cup|First round]]\n|-\n|2018\u201319\n|[[2018\u201319 Albanian Second Division|Albanian Second Division]]\n|22\n|12\n|5\n|5\n|51\n|25\n|41\n|5th<small>/13</small>\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|}\n\n\n==Current squad==\n{{updated|27 September 2017}}\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=88|pos=GK|nat=ALB|name=Kleris dobra}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Orgest Tanushi}}\n{{Fs player|no=6|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Shaqir jugu}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Klejvi Spahiu}} (Captain)\n{{Fs player|no=19|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Shaqir Jugu}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Jordi Koxha}}\n{{Fs player|no=2|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Ergys Alliu}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Ernest Xhakeri}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Erando Seferi}} \n{{Fs player|no=29|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Xhoi Xhani}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Endri Goci}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Migers Sollaku}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Alban Dosku}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Serxhio Mehmeti}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Ralf Koxha}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|pos=FW|nat=ALB|name=Martin Rreshka }}\n{{Fs player|no=9|pos=FW|nat=ALB|name=Silvestro Karaj}} \n{{Fs player|no=20|pos=FW|nat=ALB|name=Kreshnik Rroca }}\n{{Fs player|no=22|pos=FW|nat=ALB|name=Ersel Dosku }}\n{{Fs player|no=21|pos=FW|nat=ALB|name=Arnold Rreshka}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==Historical list of coaches==\n{{col-begin-small}}\n{{col-2}}\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} [[Kostika Sterja]] (1992-1994)\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} [[Luan Deliu]] (1994-1997)\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} [[Ylli Hasa]] (1997-1998)\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} [[Gentian Stojku]] (Aug 2014&nbsp;- Mar 2015)\n{{col-2}}\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} [[Edmond Dalipi]] (Mar 2015&nbsp;- May 2015)\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} [[Alpin Gallo]] (Aug 2016&nbsp;- Oct 2016)\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} [[Bekim Kuli]] (Mar 2017&nbsp;- Jun 2017)\n*{{flagicon|ALB}} [[Klajdi K\u00ebnga]] (Aug 2017&nbsp;\u2013 )\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081217085316/http://www.futbollishqiptar.net/ FutbolliShqiptar.net]{{in lang|sq}}\n*[http://www.freewebs.com/albsoccer Albanian Soccer News]{{in lang|sq|en}}\n\n{{Kategoria e dyt\u00eb}}\n{{Kategoria Superiore}}\n{{Football in Albania}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sopoti}}\n[[Category:Football clubs in Albania]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1948]]\n[[Category:1948 establishments in Albania]]\n[[Category:Librazhd]]\n\n\n{{Albania-footyclub-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| nickname = Sopotar\u00ebt\n| ground =  [[Sopoti Stadium]]<br/>[[Librazhd]], [[Albania]]\n| capacity = 3,000\n| pattern_la1=TTTT\n| pattern_la2=JJJJ\n| pattern_b2=JJJJ\n| pattern_ra1=KKKKKKK\n| pattern_ra2=BBBB\n| leftarm1= 0D7301\n| leftarm2=722U2HHHH\n| body1= 0D7301\n| body2=FFFFFF\n| rightarm1= 0D7301\n| rightarm2=FFHHHHHFFFF\n| shorts1=FFFFFFFFFFFFF\n| shorts2=FFFFDFFFFFF\n| socks1= 0DO7301\n| socks2=0D78301\n| clubname = \n| image =  [[Image:Sopoti Librazhd Club Logo.svg|230px|Club crest]]\n| fullname = Klubi Sportiv Sopoti Librazhd\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1948}}\n| owntitle = President\n| owner = [[Bashkia Librazhd]] \n| chairman = [[Kastriot Gurra]] \n| manager = [[Klajdi K\u00ebnga]]\n| league = [[Albanian Second Division]]\n| season   = [[2018\u201319 Albanian Second Division|2018\u201319]]\n| position = [[Albanian Second Division]], Group A, 5th \n| pattern_b1=\n| website= \n}}\n'''KF Sopoti''' is an Albanian [[sports club]] based in [[Librazhd]]. The club currently competes in the [[Albanian Second Division]], the third tier of football in Albania.\n\n==History==\nThey were founded in 1948 under the name ''KS Albania Tabak Librazhd'', and they play their home games at the [[Sopoti Stadium]]. The club is named after the nearby [[Sopot, Albania|Sopot]] Mountain. They spent the [[1992\u201393 Albanian Superliga|1992/93]], [[1993\u201394 Albanian Superliga|1993/94]], [[1995\u201396 Albanian Superliga|1995/96]] and [[1996\u201397 Albanian Superliga|1996/97]] seasons in the [[Albanian Superliga|''Kategoria Superiore'']]. Before the 1996/97 season the changed their name back to Albania Tabak Librazhd,<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/alba97.html Albania 1996/97] - RSSSF</ref> only to change it to Sopoti Librazhd once more the next year.\n\n==Stadium==\nThe club's home ground is the multi-use [[Sopoti Stadium]] which is situated in the centre of the town next to the municipality building. The stadium which has a capacity of 3,000 spectators was built in 1964 and has been the club's home ever since. The stadium is not currently fit for use but the [[Albanian Football Association]] along with the [[Librazhd|Librazhd Municipality]] have drawn up initial plans to reconstruct the stadium in its entirety, but such plans have yet to be materialised due to a lack of funding.<ref>[http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/ngjallen-shpresat-per-stadiumin-e-librazhdit/ Ngjallen shpresat p\u00ebr stadiumin e Librazhdit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006072012/http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/ngjallen-shpresat-per-stadiumin-e-librazhdit/ |date=6 October 2014 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/sopoti-problem-ceshtja-e-stadiumit/ Sopoti, problem \u00e7\u00ebshtja e stadiumit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006092601/http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/sopoti-problem-ceshtja-e-stadiumit/ |date=6 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAs of the 2014\u201315 season the stadium does not meet the current [[Albanian Football Association]]'s standard requirements, due to the outdated and run down nature of the building as well as the field.<ref>[http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/skandal-ne-librazhd-fusha-kthehet-ne-mocal/ Skandal n\u00eb Librazhd, fusha kthehet n\u00eb \u201cmo\u00e7al\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006110520/http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-e-pare/skandal-ne-librazhd-fusha-kthehet-ne-mocal/ |date=6 October 2014 }}</ref> .In 2017-18 season Kf Sopoti will play in home stadium with new coach the 25 years old ex player of Sopoti Mr. Klajdi K\u00ebnga and the players will be from age groups .\n\n==Recent seasons==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=9|League\n!rowspan=2 width=\"30\"|[[Croatian Football Cup|Cup]]\n|-\n!Division\n!width=\"25\"|P\n!width=\"25\"|W\n!width=\"25\"|D\n!width=\"25\"|L\n!width=\"25\"|F\n!width=\"25\"|A\n!width=\"25\"|Pts\n!width=\"40\"|Pos\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|[[2017\u201318 Albanian Second Division|Albanian Second Division]]\n|24\n|6\n|5\n|13\n|35\n|44\n|23\n|10th<small>/14<small/>\n|[[2018\u201319 Albanian Cup|First round]]\n|-\n|2018\u201319\n|[[2018\u201319 Albanian Second Division|Albanian Second Division]]\n|22\n|12\n|5\n|5\n|51\n|25\n|41\n|5th<small>/13<small/>\n|align=center|\u2014\n|-\n|}\n\n\n==Current squad==\n{{updated|27 September 2017}}\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=88|pos=GK|nat=ALB|name=Kleris dobra}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Orgest Tanushi}}\n{{Fs player|no=6|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Shaqir jugu}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Klejvi Spahiu}} (Captain)\n{{Fs player|no=19|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Shaqir Jugu}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Jordi Koxha}}\n{{Fs player|no=2|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Ergys Alliu}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|pos=DF|nat=ALB|name=Ernest Xhakeri}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Erando Seferi}} \n{{Fs player|no=29|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Xhoi Xhani}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Endri Goci}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|pos=MF|nat=ALB|name=Migers Sollaku}}